#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:1
msgid "Feature Name: edition_2021"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:2
msgid "Start Date: 2021-02-19"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:3
msgid ""
"RFC PR: [rust-lang/rfcs#3085](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/3085)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:4
msgid ""
"Rust Issue: [rust-lang/rust#85811](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/85811)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:9
msgid ""
"This RFC describes the plan for the 2021 Edition. It supersedes [RFC 2052]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2052-epochs.md). The "
"proposed 2021 Edition is intentionally more limited than the 2018 Edition. "
"Rather than representing a major marketing push, the 2021 Edition represents "
"a chance for us to introduce changes that would otherwise be backwards "
"incompatible. It is meant to be marketed in many ways as something closer to "
"\"just another release\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:11
msgid "Key points include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:13
msgid ""
"Editions are used to introduce changes into the language that would "
"otherwise have the potential to break existing code, such as the "
"introduction of a new keyword."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:14
msgid ""
"Editions are never allowed to split the ecosystem. We only permit changes "
"that still allow crates in different editions to interoperate."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:15
msgid ""
"Editions are named after the year in which they occur (e.g., Rust 2015, Rust "
"2018, Rust 2021)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:16
msgid ""
"When we release a new edition, we also release tooling to automate the "
"migration of crates. Some manual work may be required but that should be "
"uncommon."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:17
msgid ""
"The nightly toolchain offers \"preview\" access to upcoming editions, so "
"that we can land work that targets future editions at any time."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:18
msgid ""
"We maintain an Edition Migration Guide that offers guidance on how to "
"migrate to the next edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:19
msgid ""
"Whenever possible, new features should be made to work across all editions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:21
msgid ""
"This RFC is meant to establish the high-level purpose of an edition and to "
"describe how the RFC feels to end users. It intentionally avoids detailed "
"policy discussions, which are deferred to the appropriate subteams "
"(compiler, lang, dev-tools, etc) to figure out."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:25
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:28
msgid ""
"The plan for editions was laid out in [RFC 2052](https://github.com/rust-"
"lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2052-epochs.md) and Rust had its first edition in "
"2018. This effort was in many ways a success but also resulted in a lot of "
"stress on the Rust organization as a whole. This RFC proposes a different "
"model for the 2021 Edition. Depending on our experience, we may opt to "
"continue with this model in the future, or we may wish to make changes for "
"future editions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:30
msgid ""
"The following sections describe various \"guiding principles\" concerning "
"editions. They are ordered with a loose notion of priority, starting with "
"the most important and ending with the least. (This may be relevant in case "
"of conflicting principles.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:32
msgid "Editions enable \"stability without stagnation\""
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:34
msgid ""
"The release of Rust 1.0 established [\"stability without stagnation\"]"
"(https://blog.rust-lang.org/2014/10/30/Stability.html) as a core Rust "
"deliverable. Ever since the 1.0 release, the rule for Rust has been that "
"once a feature has been released on stable, we are committed to supporting "
"that feature for all future releases."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:36
msgid ""
"There are times, however, when it is useful to be able to make small changes "
"in the surface syntax of Rust that would not otherwise be backwards "
"compatible. The most obvious example is introducing a new keyword, which "
"would invalidate existing names for variables and so forth. Even when such "
"changes do not \"feel\" backwards incompatible, they still have the "
"potential to break existing code. If we were to make such changes, people "
"would quickly find that existing programs stopped compiling."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:38
msgid ""
"**Editions** are the mechanism we use to square this circle. When we wish to "
"release a feature that would otherwise be backwards incompatible, we do so "
"as part of a new **Rust edition**. Editions are opt-in, and so existing "
"crates do not see these changes until they explicitly migrate over to the "
"new edition. New crates created by cargo always default to the most recent "
"edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:40
msgid "Guide-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:43
msgid ""
"The following sections define the goals and design principles that we will "
"use for the 2021 edition, and potentially for future editions. The ordering "
"is significant, with earlier sections taking precedence in the case of a "
"conflict. (For example, it's more important that users are able to control "
"when they adopt the new edition than it is for the edition to be rapidly "
"adopted.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:45
msgid "Editions do not split the ecosystem"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:47
msgid ""
"The most important rule for editions is that crates in one edition can "
"interoperate seamlessly with crates compiled in other editions. This ensures "
"that the decision to migrate to a newer edition is a \"private one\" that "
"the crate can make without affecting others, apart from the fact that it "
"affects the version of rustc that is required, akin to making use of any new "
"feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:49
msgid ""
"The requirement for crate interoperability implies some limits on the kinds "
"of changes that we can make in an edition. In general, changes that occur in "
"an edition tend to be \"skin deep\". All Rust code, regardless of edition, "
"is ultimately compiled to the same internal representation within the "
"compiler."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:51
msgid "Edition migration is easy and largely automated"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:53
msgid ""
"Our goal is to make it easy for crates to upgrade to newer editions. "
"Whenever we release a new edition, we also release tooling to automate the "
"migration. The tooling is not necessarily perfect: it may not cover all "
"corner cases, and manual changes may still be required. The tooling tries "
"hard to avoid changes to semantics that could affect the correctness or "
"performance of the code."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:55
msgid ""
"In addition to tooling, we also maintain an Edition Migration Guide that "
"covers the changes that are part of an edition. This guide will describe the "
"change and give pointers to where people can learn more about it. It will "
"also cover any corner cases or details that people should be aware of. The "
"guide serves both as an overview of the edition, but also as a quick "
"troubleshooting reference if people encounter problems with the automated "
"tooling."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:57
msgid "Users control when they adopt the new edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:59
msgid ""
"Part of making edition migration easy is ensuring that users can choose when "
"they wish to upgrade. We recognize that many users, particularly production "
"users, will need to schedule time to manage an Edition upgrade as part of "
"their overall development cycle."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:61
msgid ""
"We also want to enable upgrading to be done in a gradual fashion, meaning "
"that it is possible to migrate a crate module-by-module in separate steps, "
"with the final move to the new edition happening only when all modules are "
"migrated. This is done by ensuring that there is always an \"intersection\" "
"that is compatible with both the edition N and its successor N+1."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:63
msgid "Rust should feel like \"one language\""
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:65
msgid ""
"Editions introduce backwards incompatible changes to Rust, which in turn "
"introduces the risk that Rust begins to feel like a language with many "
"dialects. We want to avoid the experience that people come to a Rust project "
"and feel unsure about what a given piece of code means or what kinds of "
"features they can use. This is why we prefer year-based editions (e.g., Rust "
"2018, Rust 2021) that group together a number of changes, rather than fine-"
"grained opt-in; year-based editions can be succinctly described, and ensure "
"that when you go to a codebase, it is relatively easy to determine what set "
"of features is available."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:67
msgid "Uniform behavior across editions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:69
msgid ""
"Pursuant to the goal of having Rust feel like \"one language\", we generally "
"prefer uniform behavior across all editions of Rust, so long as it can be "
"achieved without compromising other design goals. This means for example "
"that if we add a new feature that is backwards compatible, it should be made "
"available in all editions. Similarly, if we deprecate a pattern that we "
"think is problematic, it should be deprecated across all editions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:71
msgid "Having uniform behavior across editions has several benefits:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:73
msgid ""
"Reducing technical debt: the compiler is simpler if it has to consider fewer "
"cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:74
msgid ""
"Minimizing cognitive overload: we want to avoid users having to think too "
"much about what edition they are in. We would prefer that all Rust code "
"feels the same, no matter what edition it is using, although we are willing "
"to compromise on this principle if the benefits are large."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:75
msgid ""
"Even when changes alter core parts of Rust, we are often able to introduce "
"parts of those changes across all editions, which helps us to achieve more "
"uniformity. For example, the `crate::foo::bar` paths introduced in Rust 2018 "
"are also available on Rust 2015, since that syntax had no meaning before."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:77
msgid "Editions are meant to be adopted"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:79
msgid ""
"Our goal is to see all Rust users adopt the new edition, just as we would "
"generally prefer for people to move to the \"latest and greatest\" ways of "
"using Rust once they are available. Pursuant to the previously stated "
"principles, we don't force the edition on our users, but we do feel free to "
"encourage adoption of the edition through other means. For example, the "
"default edition for new projects will always be the newest one. When "
"designing features, we are generally willing to require edition adoption to "
"gain access to the full feature or the most ergonomic forms of the feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:81
msgid "Reference-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:84
msgid "Edition cadence not specified"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:86
msgid ""
"This RFC explicitly does not attempt to specify the cadence for releasing "
"editions. Historically, they have occurred every 3 years, if one considers "
"Rust 1.0 (released in 2015) to be the \"original edition\". Our expectation "
"is that after Rust 2021 is shipped, we will use the experiences from Rust "
"2018 and Rust 2021 to review how editions are working and potentially "
"establish a cadence for future editions (or perhaps make other changes to "
"the edition system)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:88
msgid ""
"There are various constraints on the timing of editions that have been "
"identified over time:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:90
msgid ""
"Even if it's automated, migrating to a new edition can require a significant "
"investment of time, particularly for production users with many crates. We "
"don't wish to release editions at a rate that makes it hard for such users "
"to keep up."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:91
msgid ""
"At the same time, we don't wish to wait too long in between editions. We "
"want to maintain the spirit of Rust's train model, so that folks don't feel "
"a \"rush\" to get work done by any particular deadline."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:92
msgid ""
"Having a generally known time when editions will be released is helpful in "
"planning feature development."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:93
msgid ""
"We do not wish to release an empty edition. Sometimes there simply won't be "
"any backwards incompatible changes and thus no reason to issue an edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:95
msgid "Definition: migration"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:97
msgid ""
"**Migrations** are the \"breaking changes\" introduced by the edition; of "
"course, since editions are opt-in, existing code does not actually break."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:99
msgid "Definition: migration lint"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:101
msgid ""
"Migrations typically come with one or more **migration lints**. Each lint "
"warns about code that will need to change in order to move to the new "
"edition. The lints typically contain \"suggestions\", which is a diff that "
"can be applied to make the code work in the new edition. In some cases, the "
"rewrite may be too complex for the lint to make a suggestion. In addition, "
"some suggestions are marked as \"not machine applicable\", if they are not "
"known to be semantics preserving."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:103
msgid "Default edition for new projects"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:105
msgid ""
"The default edition for new projects created within cargo or other tooling "
"will be 2021."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:107
msgid "RFCs that propose edition changes"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:109
msgid ""
"RFCs that propose migrations should include details about how the migration "
"between editions will work. This migration should be described in sufficient "
"detail that the relevant teams can assess the feasibility of the migration. "
"It will often make sense to consult the compiler team on this question "
"specifically."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:111
msgid ""
"To perform this evaluation, an RFC proposing a migration should enumerate "
"the situations that will no longer compile with the change."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:112
msgid ""
"For each such situation, it should describe what suggestions will be made to "
"modify the user's code such that it works on both the old and new edition. "
"Optionally, the description may include \"idiom lints\" that run only in the "
"new edition in order to make the code more idiomatic."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:113
msgid ""
"Alternatively, if that scenario is deemed unlikely, the RFC can state that "
"this sort of code will not be automatically ported between editions. It "
"should then describe if it is possible to at least issue a warning that the "
"code will no longer work or will change meaning in the new edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:115
msgid "Tooling workflow"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:117
msgid "The expected workflow for upgrading to a new edition is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:119
msgid ""
"**Prepare to upgrade:** Run `cargo fix --edition`: This will automatically "
"prepare your code to be upgraded to next edition by applying any suggestions "
"from the migration lints."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:120
msgid ""
"For example, if your code is in Rust 2018, this will prepare you to move to "
"the 2021 edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:121
msgid ""
"Note that `cargo fix` does not actually move your code to the new edition. "
"Instead, it produces code that works in both the old and the new edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:122
msgid ""
"This allows people to upgrade and fix things in a \"piecemeal\" fashion. "
"Because of this, however, the code produced by these suggestions is not "
"always the most idiomatic, as it is not able to take advantage of features "
"from the new edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:123
msgid ""
"The expectation is that `cargo fix` should be able to fix the majority of "
"crates out there, but it is not required that the tooling is able to handle "
"every case. As long as code does not occur frequently in the wild, it is "
"acceptable for the automated suggestions to be inapplicable to edge cases. "
"The metrics section in this RFC includes some guidelines for how to measure "
"this."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:124
msgid ""
"**Upgrade:** Edit your cargo.toml to include `edition = \"2021\"` instead of "
"the older edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:125
msgid ""
"The code should still build, but it may be necessary to make some fixes or "
"other changes."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:126
msgid ""
"**Cleanup:** After upgrading, you should run `cargo fix` again. This second "
"step will apply any remaining changes that are only possible in the new "
"edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:127
msgid ""
"In some cases, these lints may be cleaning up \"non-idiomatic\" code "
"produced by a migration."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:128
msgid ""
"**Manual changes:** As the final step, resolve any remaining lints or errors "
"manually (hopefully these will be quite limited). Idiom lints, in "
"particular, may not have automated suggestions, though you can always add an "
"`#![allow]` at the crate level to silence them if you are in a hurry."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:130
msgid "Specifying edition changes and migration plans"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:132
msgid ""
"Any RFC or other proposal that will cause code that used to compile on "
"edition `N` no longer compiles on edition `N+1` must include details of how "
"the \"current edition\" for that change is determined as well a migration "
"plan."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:134
msgid "Determining the current edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:136
msgid ""
"Although there is an \"ambient\" edition for the crate that is specified as "
"part of `Cargo.toml`, individual bits of code can be tied to earlier "
"editions due to the interactions of macros. For example, if a Rust 2021 "
"crate invokes a macro from a Rust 2018 crate, the body of that macro may be "
"interpreted using Rust 2018 rules. For this reason, whenever an edition "
"change is proposed, it's important to specify the tokens from which the "
"edition is determined."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:138
msgid ""
"As an example, if we are introducing a new keyword, then the edition will be "
"taken from the keyword itself. If we were to make a change to the semantics "
"of the `+` operator, we might say that the current edition is determined "
"from the `+` token. This way, if a macro author were to write `$a + $b`, "
"then this expression would use the edition rules from the macro definition "
"(which contained the `+` token). Additions that defined in the `$a` "
"expression would use the edition from which `$a` was derived."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:140
msgid "Migration plans"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:142
msgid ""
"These migration plans should be structured as the answer to three questions; "
"these questions are designed to compartmentalize review and implementation."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:144
msgid "The three questions are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:146 src/3085-edition-2021.md:155
msgid ""
"What code patterns no longer compile (or change meaning) in the new edition?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:147 src/3085-edition-2021.md:163
msgid "Which code patterns will you migrate from the old to the new edition?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:148
msgid "This should be some subset of the answer to the first question."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:149 src/3085-edition-2021.md:171
msgid "What is your plan to migrate each code pattern?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:150
msgid ""
"The plan should include automated suggestions targeting the intersection of "
"Edition N and Edition N+1."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:151
msgid ""
"The plan may also include lints specific to Edition N+1 that will cleanup "
"the code to make it more idiomatic."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:153
msgid "More details on these questions follow."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:157
msgid ""
"The RFC should list **all** known code patterns that are affected by the "
"change in edition, either because they no longer compile or because their "
"meaning changes. This should include unusual breakage that is not expected "
"in practice."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:159
msgid ""
"Answering this question is not a commitment to automatically migrate every "
"instance of these code patterns, but it is important for this research to be "
"done during the design phase such that it can be considered when evaluating "
"migration strategies."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:161
msgid ""
"Listing these code patterns allows us to make sure the migration is premised "
"on the full set of breakages. This helps avoid confusion where people don't "
"recognize what code may be affected."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:165
msgid ""
"The proposal should then declare what its intended scope for migration is. "
"This may involve declaring some of the listed breakages as out of scope."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:167
msgid ""
"Historically we have considered macro-heavy code to be something that "
"edition migrations can try to fix but are not expected to be successful in "
"working on. Similarly, there may be niche breakages that the designers do "
"not expect to crop up in practice."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:169
msgid ""
"Listing all this helps correctly set expectations, and also gives people a "
"venue to discuss whether the choice of scope is correct without having to "
"glean the scope from the design of the migrations. Furthermore, if we later "
"discover that an out-of-scope breakage is actually somewhat common, this "
"provides a clean separation in the proposal to work on addressing this."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:173
msgid ""
"The proposal should then contain a detailed design for one or more "
"compatibility lints that migrate code such that it will compile on both "
"editions. Such lints can be specified by listing the kinds of code they "
"should catch, and the changes that should be programmatically made to them."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:175
msgid ""
"If needed, the proposal may also contain designs for idiom lints that clean "
"up the migrated code (potentially making it compile on the new edition only)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:177
msgid ""
"Listing all of this helps allow reviewers to check if the lints seem "
"feasible and whether they do indeed cover the desired code patterns. It also "
"allows implementors to implement a concrete migration plan rather than "
"having to come up with one on the spot."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:179
msgid "Limits of edition changes"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:181
msgid ""
"Edition changes cannot make arbitrary changes. First and foremost, they must "
"always respect the constraint that crates in different editions can "
"interoperate; this implies that the changes must be \"skin deep\". In terms "
"of the compiler implementation, what this means is that Edition can change "
"the way that concrete Rust syntax is desugared into MIR (the compiler's "
"internal representation for Rust code), but doesn't change the semantics of "
"MIR itself (or trait matching, etc)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:183
msgid "Some examples of changes the editions can make:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:185
msgid "Introducing a new keyword, as with `async-await`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:186
msgid ""
"This change comes with automated tooling that rewrites identifiers using "
"that keyword to use `r#` form."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:187
msgid ""
"Changing closures so that they capture precise paths, rather than entire "
"variables, as in [RFC 2229](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/2229)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:188
msgid ""
"This change comes with automated tooling that modifies closures to capture "
"entire variables when necessary."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:189
msgid ""
"In MIR, closures are desugared into structs with fields, so all editions can "
"still target the same internal representation."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:190
msgid "Changing the prelude for Rust code."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:191
msgid "Changing type inference rules."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:192
msgid ""
"For example, the current `AsRef` trait allows one to write `let x: _ = y."
"as_ref()` and have the compiler infer the type of `x` based on the set of "
"applicable `AsRef` impls. This results in frequent breakage when new impls "
"are added. While this is permitted by our semver rules, it is not desirable. "
"We could theoretically introduce a change to newer editions that forbids "
"this sort of inference and requires an explicit type of `x`, while keeping "
"the behavior the same for older editions. Since MIR contains explicit types "
"everywhere, there is a common IR."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:194
msgid "Some examples of changes editions cannot make:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:196
msgid "Loosening the coherence rules in just one edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:197
msgid ""
"Coherence is a \"zero sum\" global property that states that there are no "
"two impls that apply to the same types. This property must hold across all "
"crates, regardless of edition, so we can't tweak the rules in just crates in "
"the 2021 Edition to permit impls that would be disallowed in 2018 crates. If "
"we did so, then crates in the 2018 Edition could add the impl under the old "
"rules, and another crate in the 2021 Edition could add the same impl per the "
"new rules, resulting in an error."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:201
msgid "Access to the 2021 edition on nightly"
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:203
msgid ""
"The nightly compiler will make a 2021 edition available in an unstable form. "
"This will allow us to build and test the migrations for various features "
"that will be part of the 2021 edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/3085-edition-2021.md:205
msgid ""
"**Warning:** It is not recommended for crates, even nightly-only crates, to "
"adopt the 2021 Edition too early. Like any unstable feature, the future "
"editions can change without notice and crates are expected to keep up. "
"Furthermore, the automatic migrations are designed to be used exactly once; "
"if a crate C is migrated from Edition X to Edition Y, and then new features "
"or migrations are added to Edition Y, the crate C may not be able to access "
"those new migrations and the changes may have to be done manually."
msgstr ""

